Dr. Lamont O. Repollet was appointed Acting Commissioner of the New Jersey Department of Education by the New Jersey State Board of Education on January 29, 2018.
From 2014 to 2018, Dr. Repollet served as superintendent of the Asbury Park School District. Throughout his career in education, Dr. Repollet has earned honors and recognition from numerous civic and charitable organizations. Most recently, Dr. Repollet was recognized as Educator of the Year by the Chi Sigma Chapter of Phi Beta Sigma Fraternity, Inc.
We are so appreciative for Dr. Repollet's contributions to the field of education and his dedication to ensuring all children have the opportunities they deserve üåüüôèüèø

post_text:
Few athletes are able to transcend their sport to become cultural icons like #MuhammadAli did. The Heavyweight Boxing Champion became a symbol of perseverance and integrity through his protests of the Vietnam War and his outspoken criticism of the racist policies of the government.
Ali showed us that you can represent your country with pride while also calling out the injustices one faces and demonstrated the necessity of being an actively engaged citizen.
Muhammad Ali paved the way for athletes to feel empowered to speak out and we continue to learn from his strength even today üåü‚úäüèø
text:
Few athletes are able to transcend their sport to become cultural icons like #MuhammadAli did. The Heavyweight Boxing Champion became a symbol of perseverance and integrity through his protests of the Vietnam War and his outspoken criticism of the racist policies of the government.
Ali showed us that you can represent your country with pride while also calling out the injustices one faces and demonstrated the necessity of being an actively engaged citizen.
Muhammad Ali paved the way for athletes to feel empowered to speak out and we continue to learn from his strength even today üåü‚úäüèø

A living legend and media mogul, Oprah Winfrey gained national attention with her daytime talkshow, which brought together people across all social classes to discuss topics in pop culture, politics, and more.
By starting her own production company along with other business ventures, Winfrey would eventually become the first black female billionaire.
A woman of many talents, we can see Winfrey on our TVs, movie screens, and magazines, earning nominations at the Academy Awards, and interviewing iconic personalities in American culture.
If Oprah has taught us anything, it's that a person can wear many hats and wear them all very well.
We admire Oprah for being an example of perseverance, dedication, and grace for us all üôèüèø

For many, writer and poet #JamesBaldwin most eloquently articulated their unique experiences living a segregated, unequal society.
Whether through his works of fiction or his poignant essays, Baldwin was able to artfully convey the pain, the struggle, and on the other end, the joy, and the glory of being one's true self.
Baldwin's influence permeates through today's films and literature depicting African-American life, and is often cited as the source of inspiration for many American artists across all mediums.
We are grateful to have shared space with this exceptional being üôèüèø‚úäüèø #BHM

While #HillaryClinton was celebrating her historic democratic presidential nomination, the rest of us remembered #ShirleyChisholm ‚úäüèø
Shirley Chisholm was not only the first African-American to launch a presidential campaign with a major political party, she was also the first black woman to be elected to Congress when she won her race to represent New York's 12th District in the House of Representatives. Chisholm went on to serve her district for 7 terms.
During her tenure, Chisholm would become a founding member of both the Congressional Black Caucus and the National Women's Political.

Thank you to Shirley Chisholm for expanding programs that helped women, minorities, and poor people live better lives. You showed us what a real leader is capable of and for that we are forever indebted üôèüèøüá∫üá∏
#BlackHistoryMonth #BlackHistoryIsAmericanHistory

Before becoming the first African-American Supreme Court justice, attorney #ThurgoodMarshall took on a number of cases challenging legalized forms of racism. In fact, no other attorney had tried as many cases as Marshall before the Supreme Court. Perhaps you recognize him from your history books: Marshall was the lead attorney who tried and won the landmark Brown vs. Board of Education case, which abolished segregation in American schools.

Thanks to the tenacity and dedication of Thurgood Marshall, Black Americans and other minority groups gained the courage to challenge the laws and systems that have intentionally held them back. We are eternally grateful for this hero's contributions to our American Dream ‚úäüèøüá∫üá∏
#BlackHistoryIsAmericanHistory

Filmmaker and actor, #SidneyPoitier has been a source of inspiration for black artists since his breakout performance as Gregory Miller in "Blackout Jungle."
Poitier became the the first African-American to be nominated in the Best Actor category at the Academy Awards in 1959, and would later win the award in 1964 for his role in "Lilies in the Field."
While receiving the award in 2002 as only the second African-American to win, actor #DenzelWashington dedicated his speech to Poitier by saying, " I'll always be chasing you, Sidney. I'll always be following in your footsteps. There's nothing I would rather do, sir. Nothing I would rather do. God bless you. God bless you."

God Bless Sidney Poitier and his legacy ‚úäüèø #BlackHistoryMonth

post_text:
Happy Birthday to Rosa Parks who would have been 107 years old today! üéà
Rosa Parks became a recognized civil rights activist for her famous refusal to give up her seat to a white passenger on a public bus in Montgomery, Alabama, setting the stage for the citywide Montgomery Bus Boycott that lasted over a year.
Parks had been an activist for years prior to her controversial arrest, working with her local chapter of the NAACP and getting elected to an administrative position within the organization.
Her arrest and the subsequent protests marked a major shift in civil rights activism for the African-American community, from which they never turned back.
We are eternally grateful to have shared the earth with such a remarkable woman. Rest in Power üôå

post_text:
Did you know that #BlackHistoryMonth was originally only a week?
Carter G. Woodson, who is accredited as one of the first scholars of African-American history, recognized there was a need to educate Americans on the full history of our nation after he himself studied history at the University of Chicago and Harvard University.
(It wasn't until 1976 that President Gerald Ford officially designated February as Black History Month.)

Throughout this month, we will highlight Americans who have persevered despite prejudices to achieve greatness. We hope you will share with us in learning and growing from their example so that we may continue to revise our history as it should be written. üåü
